<button class="accordion">What is mental health?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Mental health is the level of psychological well-being or an absence of mental illness. It is the state of someone who is functioning at a satisfactory level of emotional and behavioural adjustment.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is a mental health training course?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>This 'Mental Health Awareness' training raises awareness of mental ill-health, particularly stress, depression and anxiety. This training serves as a guide for daily wellbeing-management, which aims to remove the stigma surrounding mental health. Additionally, this training enables you to identify, understand, and respond to signs of addictions and mental illnesses.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/products/mental-health-awareness-online-training-course-cpduk-accredited?variant=25510092048"><font color="green"><u> Click here for Online Mental Health Awareness Training Course.</u></font></a></p><p></p></div>

<button class="accordion">What do you mean by mental health?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Mental health includes emotional, psychological, and social well-being. It affects how people think, feel, and act. It also helps determine how people handle stress, relate to others, and make daily life decisions.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the difference between mental health and mental illness?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Sometimes, people use mental health and mental illness as if they mean the same thing. However, they do not. Everyone has mental health, just like everyone has health. Mental illness is an illness the effects that way people think, feel, behave, or interact with others.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/collections/mental-health-courses-training-online-mental-health-courses"><font color="green"><u> Click here for more online mental health courses and training.</u></font></a></p><p></p></div>

<button class="accordion">What are some types of mental disorders?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Below is a list of the different types of mental disorder:</p>
<li> Anxiety disorders, including panic disorder, obsessive-compulsive disorder, post-traumatic stress disorder, and phobias</li>
<li> Depression, bipolar disorder, and other mood disorders</li>
<li> Eating disorders</li>
<li> Personality disorders</li>
<li> Psychotic disorders, including schizophrenia.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is poor mental health?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Mental health problems are health conditions that are characterised by alterations in thinking, mood or behaviour. On the other hand, good mental health is more than the absence of problems. Finding it difficult to manage how we think, feel, act, or how to manage daily stresses could be a sign of poor mental health.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the most difficult mental illness?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Personality disorders are among the most challenging forms of mental illness to treat. Often, people with these disorders do not seek help because they can function in their day-to-day lives.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is Borderline Personality Disorder?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD) is a condition characterised by difficulties regulating emotion. People with BPD feel emotions intensely and for extended periods. They find it hard to return to a stable baseline after an emotionally triggering event.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the 5 signs of mental illness?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The five warning signs of mental illness include:</p>
<li> Long-lasting sadness or irritability</li>
<li> Extremely high and low moods</li>
<li> Excessive fear, worry, or anxiety</li>
<li> Social withdrawal</li>
<li> Dramatic changes in eating or sleeping habits.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">How do you know you have poor mental health?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Signs of poor mental health include:</p>
<li> Poor concentration</li>
<li> Being easily distracted</li>
<li> Worrying more</li>
<li> Finding it hard to make decisions</li>
<li> Feeling less interested in day-to-day activities</li>
<li> Low mood</li>
<li> Feeling overwhelmed by things</li>
<li> Tearfulness.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What factors affect mental health?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The following factors could potentially result in a period of poor mental health. These include:</p>
<li> Childhood abuse, trauma, or neglect</li>
<li> Social isolation or loneliness</li>
<li> Experiencing discrimination and stigma</li>
<li> Social disadvantage, poverty or debt</li>
<li> Bereavement (losing someone close to you)</li>
<li> Severe or long-term stress.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What mental disorder is the most dangerous?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Anorexia is the most lethal psychiatric disorder, carrying a sixfold increased risk of death. It is four times the death risk from major depression. The odds are even worse for people first diagnosed with anorexia in their 20s.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What makes you mentally unstable?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Mental illnesses, in general, are thought to be caused by a variety of genetic and environmental factors:</p>
<li> Inherited traits</li>
<li> Environmental exposures before birth</li>
<li> Brain chemistry.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What does it mean to be mentally unstable?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>If you are unstable emotionally, you might be ecstatically happy one minute and depressed and angry the next. To be unstable is to lack stability, meaning things could change without warning, like an unstable bookshelf that is likely to fall.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is workplace mental health?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>A psychologically healthy workplace is one that actively works to prevent harm to worker psychological health, including in negligent, reckless, or intentional ways, and promotes mental well-being.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the social factors in mental health?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Most aspects of mental illness and psychological well‚Äêbeing result from social factors, such as gender, social class, race and ethnicity, and household pattern. This includes social institutions, such as disability and social security systems, labour markets, and health care organisations.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the different methods to use for the treatment of mental disorders?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Below is a list for the treatment of mental disorders:</p>
<li> Somatotherapy</li>
<li> Psychotherapy</li>
<li> Psychoanalysis</li>
<li> Gestalt therapy.</li>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What was the first drug used to treat mental illness?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>In 1948, they used lithium as a psychiatric medicine. In fact, one of the most important discoveries was chlorpromazine, an antipsychotic drug for a patient in 1952.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Is the Mental Health Act a law?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>The Mental Health Act is the law that describes what should happen when someone who is living with a mental illness needs treatment and protection for themselves or others. A person experiencing a mental illness can receive treatment and support through a voluntary or involuntary process.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What rights do people with mental health have?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>People with mental illness are entitled to fair treatment, and they should:</p>
<li> Be treated with respect and dignity</li>
<li> Have their privacy protected</li>
<li> Receive services appropriate for their age and culture</li>
<li> Understand treatment options and alternatives</li>
<li> Get the care that does not discriminate based on age, race, or type of illness.</li>
</div>
